data.text:
The Central Board of Film Certification (CBFC), formerly known as Central Board of Film Censors, is a statutory film-certification body in the Ministry of Information and Broadcasting[1] of the Government of India. It is responsible for the certification and censorship of films released within India.[2][3]

The CBFC has its headquarters in Mumbai (pre-1995 known as Bombay) and regional offices in eight Indian cities, namely, Bangalore, Chennai (pre-1996 known as Madras), Cuttack, Hyderabad, Kolkata (pre-2001 known as Calcutta), New Delhi, and Thiruvananthapuram (pre-1991 known as Trivandrum).[4]

Central Board of Film Censors[]

1951-July, 1969[]

August, 1969-June, 1983; June, 1983 - 1991 (secondary)[]

Some films released post June 1983 continued to use the Censors version of the film certificate with the word being crossed out by a row of X's and the word Certification being written on top or beside the crossed-out word - those film certificates are included here.

Central Board of Film Certification[]

June, 1983-December 31, 1995[]

Main article: Central Board of Film Certification Rating IDs/June, 1983-December 31, 1995

January, 1996-December, 2011; December, 2011 - 20?? (secondary)[]

During this time, the certificates have received a major upgrade.

On the top it says Government of India, and in the bottom it shows the text Central Board of Film Certification, the top right corner shows the State Emblem of India[5], in the left shows the certificate number, film name, date, and gauge. The middle shows the rating symbol for the movie, and the right shows the category's name, length, and Mts Reels. Below that, there is some text saying this:

"After examination of the film by the members of the Examining Committee/Revising Committee/Film Certification Appellate Tribunal, the Board hereby certifies that the film is fit for (rating description) listed in Part II on the reverse."

Below that is the people who helped classify the film, text saying Further certified that the excisions and modficiations imposed by the Board have actually been carried out., the applicant and the producer of the film, and a chairman signature.

It is quite noticeable that most of the certificates released in this period have the text Revising Committee/Film Certification Appellate Tribunal in Hindi, English, or both crossed out.

Some certificates have their paper color-coded, yellow for U, cyan for U/A, and pink for A (although some films desaturate the color to make it red).

January, 2012-January, 2018[]

During this time, the certificates are now computer generated.

Due to the halt of films being released on VHS and moved on to DVD, the gauge and Mts Reels were removed and Length was renamed Duration.

The text for the certificate info is now Arial, and the symbol font is now Arial Bold Rounded.

And finally, the text Revising Committee/Film Certification Appellate Tribunal was removed.

February, 2018-December, 2019[]

Some films use an alternate version of the certificates on top where the text for the info is Verdana and the text for the film rating symbol is regular Arial Bold. (Although the U/A version combines with the Hindi rating information text)
